The Texas Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers (TACRAO) will host a virtual college night for MISD high school students on Tuesday, Sept. 22 from 6–8 p.m.

The event offers students the opportunity to glean information from a vast array of collegiate institutions in one virtual setting.

“MISD is proud to offer our students this alternative way to experience College Night,” said MISD Senior Director of Guidance and Counseling Jennifer Akins. “Over 300 colleges and universities will have a virtual presence!

Registration is required, and students can access the registration page by clicking here:

MISD Parents,

SSO, Canvas, Seesaw and Zoom have been restored and are now available for use to complete assignments and homework over the weekend. MISD is continuing to address the issues affecting other district services, such as email and eSchool, and we expect all MISD online resources to be restored by this weekend.

For students learning virtually who missed instruction today as a result of this issue, we understand this was out of your control, and teachers will work with you to complete any missed lessons or assignments. Absences recorded during this interruption of service will not be counted towards a student’s 90 percent attendance requirement. We apologize for any inconvenience this has caused and appreciate your patience during this challenging situation.

Parents of students in PreK–2nd grade who checked out a laptop at the beginning of the school year:

If your PreK—2nd grade student will be returning to campus to receive in-person instruction beginning Thursday, September 3, the district asks that you return his or her MISD loaner laptop. If you received a charging cable with the laptop, please return it as well. You can send the laptop with your student to turn in to the classroom teacher.

Students who remain at home and continue to receive instruction online may continue to use a loaner laptop if they have one checked out. But, MISD needs students in PreK—2nd grade who are returning for in-person instruction to bring back their borrowed devices so that they can be made available to students within the classroom.

McKinney, Texas- Four years ago, the McKinney ISD community approved a $220 million MISD school bond package—accompanied by a tax decrease—that included a wide array of projects to be completed over a five year span. Now, MISD is nearing the conclusion of those 2016 Bond projects, with approximately 90 percent of the them delivered over the last four years—as well as an additional seven campus refresh projects.

Here’s an update on some of the recently completed projects:

MISD Parents,

Zoom is reporting nationwide issues that are preventing users from accessing meetings and webinars, and this is affecting some students’ ability to connect to virtual class meetings. Zoom reports that they are investigating the issue, and we will provide updates as we get more information.

We ask that students try regularly to access their class meetings throughout the day. For students who miss class time because of the Zoom outage, we want you to know that we understand this issue was out of your control, and teachers will work with students to complete any missed lessons or assignments. Absences recorded during the Zoom outage will not be counted towards a student’s 90% attendance requirement.

post_text:
Network Update:

This morning, several local districts, including MISD were experiencing network interruptions that affected our campus websites as well as access to SSO, Canvas and Seesaw due to a Region 10 network issue. We are also experiencing intermittent issues with phone service at several campuses. Region 10 has resolved the issues related to our educational platforms, however, some campuses are still experiencing intermittant phone issues.

We understand that families impacted by the technical issues may have missed virtual instruction. We want you to know that we understand this issue was out of your control, and teachers will work with students to complete any missed lessons or assignments. Absences recorded during these interruptions will not be counted towards a student’s 90% attendance requirement. We appreciate your patience as we work through these challenges.

Welcome Back! The MISD 2020–2021 school year is underway! Teachers and students kicked off the year today across MISD in what has to be the most unique start to a school year in district history. And, while they couldn’t yet meet in person, our teachers were overjoyed to greet their new students virtually and get the new school year rolling.

Parents and students, thank you for your patience as we work through some of the adjustments around virtual learning.

It’s going to be a great year!

Parents of McKinney ISD Pre-K through 2nd grade students:

Today we are holding a device pick-up for Pre-K through 2nd grade students who do not have any access to a technology device at home. If you already have a device such as a laptop or iPad at home, we are asking that you do not pick up a device today. We are currently only providing devices for families with no access to a computer or iPad at home.

If you already own a device at your home please do not pick one up today. We will provide additional information in the coming days regarding available devices. Thanks for your cooperation and support to ensure that all McKinney ISD students have access to technology and online learning. Have a great day!

McKinney Independent School District

New Collin College Technical Campus Offers MISD Students Dual Credit, Accelerated Pathways to 10 Career Fields

McKinney, Texas – This fall, Collin College and McKinney ISD will usher in a new era of opportunity for MISD students when the college opens its beautifully-appointed, state of the art Technical Campus located just a few miles south of McKinney.

Read the full story here — https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/article/new-collin-college-technical-campus-offers-misd-students-dual-credit-accelerated-pathways-to-10-career-fields/

The three-story, 340,000 square-foot facility will feature the newest industry-standard technology and will serve up to 7,100 traditional college and dual credit students when fully occupied.

And, it will provide an opportunity for MISD juniors and seniors to take part in a two-year, dual credit program that will allow them to earn industry certification and a year of credit toward an associate degree in one of 10 technical career areas by the time they graduate high school...

post_text:
MISD is pleased to announce that Webb Elementary Principal Kyle Luthi will move from Webb to the principal position at the McKinney ISD Disciplinary Alternative Education Program.

Click here for more — https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/press-release/webb-principal-kyle-luthi-named-principal-of-daep/

Luthi brings 18 years in education and 13 years of experience in campus leadership to this crucial role.

As Luthi looks ahead to his new position, he looks back with fondness on his time at Webb. “It has been an honor to serve the wonderful students and community of Webb Elementary,” Luthi said. “I am so grateful for the relationships and experiences that have occurred over the past 13 years, and Webb will always hold a special place in my heart.

“I look forward to working with and serving the students and staff at DAEP,” he said. “I know that together, we can make a difference in the lives of those we serve and make a positive impact on our schools and community.”

post_text:
Graduation Streaming
The MISD graduation ceremonies will be streamed live for family members who are unable to attend and for out of town friends and family. In addition, all regularly scheduled graduation speeches and performances will be pre-recorded and edited as part of the graduation video that will be available to the public following the graduations.

The graduations will be streamed live on the MISD graduation page: https://www.mckinneyisd.net/graduation/

The live stream for each graduation will begin at 9 a.m.

McKinney High School graduation will take place on Thursday, May 28; McKinney North High School graduation will take place on Friday, May 29; and the graduation for McKinney Boyd High School will be held on Saturday, May 30. Arrival times have been sent to graduates from their respective schools along with detailed instructions.

post_text:
MHS Team Wins State Engineering Competition for Second Year in a Row!
Please join us in congratulating the MHS engineering team who earned the top spot in the Texas TEAMS (Tests of Engineering Aptitude, Mathematics and Science) competition for the second year in a row! (They competed before the school closure but had to wait for the competition window to officially close and all the results to come in from across the state.)

Congratulations! Well done!

https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/article/mhs-students-earn-top-spot-in-state-engineering-competition-for-second-year-in-a-row/

The McKinney High School State Champion TEAMS team (top, from left): Andy Carithers, Davis Holdstock, Maddie Davison, Amberlynn Demko (bottom, from left) Jacob Hicks, Benjamin Merrell, Mark Taylor, Jackson Dagley (Photos courtesy of Robert Gupton)

Note: The team qualified for the national competition that was scheduled for late June, but as one might expect, that event has been cancelled.

It's National Assistant Principals Week!

We want to take a moment to say thank you to our amazing MISD assistant principals! APs have one of the most demanding jobs in education, and their leadership impacts students, teachers and the entire school community.

To recognize the significant role that APs play in the overall academic achievement of students, the National Association of Elementary School Principals has designated April 6-10, 2020, National Assistant Principals Week!

Please join us in thanking our MISD APs (and associate principals, too!) for the outstanding job they do!

post_text:
When McKinney hospitals needed supplies, the MISD Health Services Dept. responded...

As news broadcasts have made clear during recent weeks, hospitals have been running woefully short on supplies of personal protective equipment. So, last week, MISD's campus nurses collected everything except a small campus reserve from their clinic supplies: hand sanitizer, gloves, gowns, CDC-approved disinfectant wipes, N95 masks, regular masks, Super Sani wipes and hydrogen peroxide wipes. They boxed it all up at Central Office, and with the help of MISD Central Distribution Center, Facilities and Maintenance Dept. employees, loaded it up on an MISD box truck and delivered the supplies to Medical City McKinney, Baylor Scott & White Medical Center-McKinney and Methodist McKinney Hospital.

To the nurses, doctors and hospital staff in McKinney—and everywhere—who are on the front lines fighting COVID-19, we would like to offer a heartfelt thank you!

UPDATE: Important parent information regarding school March 16-20...
At this time, McKinney ISD is canceling classes for the week of March 16-20, 2020. This includes all district after school and extracurricular programs.

Due to this extended District closing, MISD will be using our two bad weather days which were scheduled for April 10th and April 27th. We will be attending school on these days.

MISD will be providing Grab & Go meals Monday-Friday, March 16-20, 2020, for any student at the following campuses: Webb, Finch, McNeil, and Slaughter. Meals will be handed out in the parking lots. Breakfast will be available from 7:30 a.m. - 8:30 a.m. and lunch will be served 11:00 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.

We are following updates and staying in close contact with city, state and health officials. All MISD updates will be posted online at mckinneyisd.net.

The STC Team wanted the students to work on social and job skills while building relationships with the staff in a fun way. Students and staff had a blast while raising money for Special Olympics!

post_text:
The McKinney ISD Board of Trustees witnessed the swearing in of new board appointee Philip Hassler at their February meeting Tuesday night at the MISD Community Event Center.

https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/article/misd-board-of-trustees-appoints-philip-hassler-to-place-2-seat/

Hassler’s appointment to the board follows the announcement in late August that Kenneth Ussery would step down from his position in Place 2 due to a change in residence that moved him beyond the Place 2 zone.

“I am honored and excited to join the McKinney ISD Board of Trustees,” said Hassler. “Former Place 2 Board Member Kenneth Ussery wonderfully served the community, and I am humbled to be stepping into his place. When looking for a place to raise our family, my wife and I specifically chose the city of McKinney for its superb schools. I look forward to joining the other Board members in serving the students, teachers, staff and administrators of McKinney ISD.”

Please join us in welcoming Philip Hassler to the MISD Board of Trustees!

post_text:
January is National Mentoring Month!

It’s difficult to overstate the importance of mentors and the impact that they have on MISD students. The time that they invest can lead to improved grades, fewer discipline referrals, improved attendance, more effective social skills and increased self-esteem. For some students, having a mentor has been the driving force that helped them push through to graduation—and on to college.

There are students out there waiting for a mentor. Maybe that mentor is you.

Consider becoming a mentor through the MISD REACH program. Find out more here: https://www.mckinneyisd.net/partners-in-education/reach/

To all of our current and past mentors, thank you for helping MISD reach one child at a time!

https://www.youtube.com/embed/dIKv3S13qBU

post_text:
It can happen in the blink of an eye…
McGowen FAC aide Lori Roof received a Certificate of Commendation at the board meeting last night from MISD Supt. Dr. Rick McDaniel and the MISD Board of Trustees for her quick response that saved the life of a McGowen student.

During the lunch period at McGowen, Lori saw that something was amiss with one of the kids at the kindergarten table. Upon investigating, she discovered that the young student was choking. Putting her SafeSchools training into action, Lori immediately employed the Heimlich maneuver, dislodged the food and averted a potentially tragic situation.

We would like to extend a heartfelt thank you to Lori Roof for her vigilance and quick response—and to all of our teachers and staff who help keep our kids safe each day!

shared_text:
McKinney Independent School District added 27 new photos.
December 20, 2019 at 2:52 PM ·

The student councils of McKinney North, MHS and Boyd came together again this year to collect and pack 825 complete turkey dinners for families in the McKinney area—175 more than they collected last year. Working together, these remarkable MISD student leaders spearheaded the annual charitable campaign that provides complete holiday meals for families who might not otherwise have one. In addition to the turkey dinners, they collected enough food to provide several hundred additional holiday meal “starter packs” as well. With help from all the student councils and North athletes, they managed to pack some 1,200 meals in about 14 minutes yesterday afternoon!

“I think it’s awesome,” said North STUCO President Joshua Shelton, “just because our motto this year is MISD Lives Kind. So, when all the student councils come together, and we all do our part, we all donate our money and we all donate our time, it just shows how McKinney can come together as a community.”

On Friday, MISD Supt. Dr. Rick McDaniel and Partners in Education Coordinator Nancy Cowlishaw visited McKinney National Airport to welcome Cirrus Aircraft as a new district business partner! Cirrus Aircraft is a highly successful aviation company whose innovations include the revolutionary Cirrus Airframe Parachute System® (CAPS®), a whole-airframe parachute system included as standard equipment on every Cirrus aircraft. To date, the CAPS system has saved 186 lives!

We are excited to explore the opportunities that lie ahead as we partner with this exciting company!

(l-r) Nancy Cowlishaw, MISD Partners in Education Coordinator; Dr. Rick McDaniel, MISD Superintendent; Jonah Santom, Managing Director, McKinney Factory Service Center; Ravi Dharnidharka, Senior Vice President, Cirrus Services & Business Development; and Jon Wright, Executive Director, Factory Service Centers

post_text:
Emerson Donates $7,000 to MHS Engineering Club

At the annual MHS STEM Advisory Board Luncheon held on Nov. 22 at MHS, Emerson Vice President of Sales Curtis Bagby presented a $7,000 check on behalf of the company to the MHS Engineering Club. For more than five years, Emerson has been an active participant in the MHS engineering program, donating funds, time and resources to the cause. Also in attendance were representatives from other vital local business partners—Raytheon, Simpson Strong-Tie, Camozzi Pneumatics, Billings Productions and Conduit Architecture—as well as MISD administrators and MISD Board Vice President Stephanie O’Dell.

Thank you to our local businesses for your support of MISD STEM programs!

Pictured here are (l-r) MHS engineering students Jackson Dagley, Ben Merrell, Caroline Potts, Maddie Davison, Andy Carithers, Curtis Bagby, Abigail McAdams, Robert Gupton, Amberlynn Demko, Jacob Hicks, Ismail Hozain and Lexi White

post_text:
MISD is pleased to welcome new Bilingual/ESL Compliance Coordinator Jeremy Hailey! He has worked in public education for eleven years with classroom experience at both the elementary and secondary levels and comes to MISD from Garland ISD where he has most recently served as their ELL Compliance Specialist. He and his wife, Betsy, and their daughter, Eloise, have recently moved to the area and are excited to get plugged in close to home. Jeremy is looking forward to the opportunity to partner with teachers, administrators and staff to further support the academic and linguistic growth of MISD's English learners. He earned his bachelor’s degree from Abilene Christian University and his master’s from Texas State University in San Marcos.

Please join us in welcoming Jeremy Hailey to MISD!

MISD and the City of McKinney are excited to announce that the community will host an exhibition and competition event during the 48th Annual Drum Corps International (DCI) Tour in July 2020 at MISD Stadium!

https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/article/mckinney-to-host-touring-drum-corps-international-competition-in-july-2020/

The event, “Marching Music Made in McKinney,” will feature several of the DCI corps, who will stop in McKinney on the road to the annual DCI World Championships in Indianapolis, Indiana, in August.

For nearly a half century, Drum Corps International, Marching Music’s Major League™, has been the leader in producing events for the world’s most elite and exclusive marching ensembles for student musicians and performers.

On Saturday, Oct. 12, 2019, the McKinney ISD Substance Use Prevention Committee will once again host “Bedrooms, Backpacks and Beyond,” a workshop the committee introduced two years ago as a resource to parents.

https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/press-release/third-annual-bedrooms-backpacks-and-beyond-event-to-offer-information-and-resources-on-substance-use/

The interactive workshop offers the opportunity to connect with other parents as well as the chance to learn from experts in the field of substance use prevention. Topics discussed will include: social media, substance use trends, community resources and how to start conversations with your kids. It's free, and no registration is required.

Details:
Saturday, October 12, 2019
McKinney High School Cafeteria
1400 Wilson Creek Pkwy
9 a.m. – 12 p.m.

The event is free, but childcare is not provided.

For more information, please contact the MISD Counseling office at 469-302-4036.

Thank you to our Adopt-a-School community volunteers who attended orientation last week with Nancy Cowlishaw from MISD Partners in Education! Volunteers from local businesses and organizations have a tremendous impact every year on the students of MISD. Dr. Rick McDaniel, MISD superintendent, stopped in to thank the volunteers for the time and resources that they invest in our students. They play a vital role in helping us meet the needs of well over 24,000 kids.

Thank you for all that you do!

McKinney ISD is pleased to once again host a low cost ZAPS PSAT/SAT test preparation seminar presented by Doorway to College Foundation that is designed to get students ready to take the PSAT/SAT.

ZAPS PSAT/SAT Test Prep Seminar
Presented by Doorway to College Foundation
McKinney Boyd High School
600 N. Lake Forest Drive
McKinney, TX 75071
Monday, Oct. 14, 2019
9 a.m. – 3 p.m.

Price: $75

Secure space for your student—Register at https://www.doorwaytocollege.com/seminarinformation/sat-seminar-details?id=8965 or call 877-927-8378, toll free, for assistance. (Please note that this class has a 45 student capacity.)

For more information, visit https://www.mckinneyisd.net/news-events/press-release/misd-to-host-low-cost-psat-sat-zaps-test-preparation-seminar-in-october-2/

14th Annual Crape Myrtle Run & Free Family Festival!
Don’t miss the 2019 Crape Myrtle Run & Free Family Festival on Saturday, Sept. 28! The event features certified, flat and very fast 5K and 10K courses plus a 1-mile fun run for kids!

And...$5 will be donated to the P.E. department of any school you name when you register! (Does not increase your registration fee.) Last year, $4,500 in grants were awarded to area schools, with McClure, Wilmeth and Evans bringing in the top three donation totals.

There will be plenty of other fun to be had in addition to running: a petting zoo, magician, face painting, obstacle course, music, lots of prizes and costume contests. So, don't miss out!

To register as a runner: http://getmeregistered.com/CMTMcKinney5K

Press fifth grader Maddie White wanted to help the kids on her campus show kindness, so she started a Kindness Club! The club’s first order of business? "On Friday, we did this switch it up recess where we got to play with someone we didn't know," Maddie said in an interview with NBC 5. "I actually played with a few new people, and I'm excited that they now know me."

We invite you to watch this heartwarming story about a girl who deals with bullies by asking them to be her study partner — and knows first hand that kindness can make a difference.

Jesse Abel is no stranger to McKinney ISD or to the role of assistant principal. After four years as assistant principal at Dowell, Abel heads to MHS this year to serve as an AP, bringing nearly 30 years of educational experience to his new campus.

Over the course of his career, Abel has served as a highly successful football and wrestling coach and has taught a broad range of sciences that includes chemistry, anatomy, meteorology and biology. In 2015, he joined the staff at Dowell as an assistant principal. Now, he moves to MHS.

Please join us in welcoming Jesse Abel to the MHS family and its proud traditions!

Laura Stinson will be familiar to the staff and students of SJMS, but they’ll find her in a new role this year as she moves from the special education department to the front office as assistant principal. She has 12 years of experience, serving in special education for Katy and Wylie ISDs before arriving at SJMS in 2016.

“After serving as the special education lead teacher at SJMS for the last three years, I am excited to be moving into a new leadership role,” said Stinson. “And, I am looking forward to a great year with our students, parents and staff!”

Please join us in welcoming Laura Stinson to this important leadership position!

post_text:
Completing Principal Holly Rogers’ admin team at Dowell this year is Russell Lewis, who comes on board alongside fellow AP Ferlanda Willis. Lewis is a former pro baseball player who went on to serve in the private sector before coming to education in 2008 when he joined the staff of McKinney North High School as an assistant baseball coach.

Since then, he has served as a football coach and history teacher at Cockrill and most recently as history department chair and 504/RTI coordinator at Evans.

Now, he joins the team at Dowell as an assistant principal.

“I am very excited to welcome Ferlanda and Russell to the Dowell family,” said Rogers. “I have had the privilege to work with both of them in the district in different capacities, and I know that they will both be a great addition to our school. The strengths that they bring will help us to continue to be the great school that we are known to be.”

Please join us in welcoming Russell Lewis to Dowell Middle School!

post_text:
We are happy to introduce Ferlanda Willis! This year, she joins the administrative team at Dowell led by Principal Holly Rogers. Willis is a talented educator who brings a wealth of experience accumulated over the course of a career spanning nearly 20 years.

During that career, she has taught kindergarten, first, second, third and fifth grades; has served as a 504 coordinator and as an instructional coach/response to intervention coordinator. Now, she steps into the role of assistant principal.

“I am truly honored to be joining the Dowell Middle School family as one of the new assistant principals,” said Willis. “I am joining a rich culture of dedication and collaboration between staff, students, parents and the community. I am excited for the 2019-2020 school year and to be part of the effort to do whatever it takes to advance the achievement of all students on our campus.”

Please join us as we welcome Ferlanda Willis to this vital leadership position!

We are pleased to welcome Justin James as the new assistant principal at Malvern Elementary, where he joins the two Rhondas — Principal Rhonda Gilliam and Asst. Principal Rhonda Hamilton - to complete the school’s administrative team! James comes to MISD from Garland ISD with a background in middle school English and AVID as well as experience as an ELAR instructional design facilitator.

“Mr. James comes with a wealth of curricular knowledge and an admirable desire to excel in all he does," said Gilliam. "He has an ability to connect with people, see the good in every situation and bring out the best in others. Our students will benefit greatly by having him in their lives.”

Please join us in welcoming Justin James to Malvern!

Allow us to introduce Kassie Halpin, assistant principal at Bennett Elementary!

Following Rachel Constantinescu’s move from the assistant principal position at Bennett Elementary to the principal job at Press Elementary during the summer, Bennett now welcomes Halpin as the school’s new assistant principal.

Halpin comes to MISD from Allen ISD and brings 11 years of experience with a background in the elementary classroom and as a campus intervention specialist—among other roles. Please join us in welcoming Kassie Halpin to the Bennett family!
